{
  "doc_id": "51036",
  "text": "AC-2 also has the ability to repress the secretion of MCP-5 and RANTES. MCP-5 is a potent monocyte active chemokine that is involved in allergic inflammation [CITATION_1] ; RANTES is also an important chemoattractant for many immune cells [CITATION_2] . Some molecules inhibit LPS-activated macrophages by interfering LPS binding to cell surface [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In this study, it is not likely that AC-2-inhibited cytokine expression is due to interferring LPS binding to its receptor TLR4 because the protein expression of TLR4 does not change after AC-2 treatment ( Figure 7A ). LPS-induced COX-2, GCSF, GM-CSF, MCP-1, sTNFRI, and TNF-α were not reduced simultaneously. Although the inhibition of COX-2 protein expression by A camphorata had been reported [CITATION_5] , there was no such bioactive constituent in this polysaccharide fraction of A camphorata. It also suggests that the bioactive compounds for inhibiting COX-2 and iNOS existed in different components of A camphorata. However, the characterization of candidate compounds that mediate the inhibition of LPS-induced NO, IL-6, IL-10, MCP-5, and RANTES secretion requires further study.",
